segments.text: Just distinctly remember that all these tables set up in Duncan and you went in there by your alphabet and there was a strategy and one of the upperclassmen talked to me about the strategy, but I was convinced at the end of it
that the rest of the semester would be easy after registration.

Registration was the hardest thing, because you'd get five of your six courses, and then the sixth one you couldn't get, so you'd have to go back and start changing things, and it was all done, it was all manual, and you were trying to get...
One of the good parts about it, I'm an early riser.
I was always an early riser.
So I liked 8 o'clock.
And not a lot of people like 8 o'clock.
And so Monday, Wednesday, Friday 8, Tuesdays and Thursdays at 8, I could get those courses.
And I liked my courses in the morning because I seemed to have a lull in the afternoon.
And so I tried to have the labs in the afternoon, the coursework in the morning.

uh... because the lab work you were active and you know that was you could kind of keep focus there but i remember uh... registration being very difficult were some of those first semester courses important as you look back now do you remember some of them some of the teachers well first you know i took 105 and you were my instructor did you also teach 106 history 106 see i don't know if i had you both years both semesters or not
But I made two B's in 105 and 106, you know, freshman history.
You know, pre-vet was kind of neat in that they were preparing you not only for the sciences, but they were also preparing you.
to run a business.
So you took English literature, you took business courses, you took history.
And I remember the only thing my daddy told me was take the hard courses and take the courses that make you think and make you write.
So when I had a choice, I was always thinking about that.
Does this course
And like I remember taking speech and they they everybody was avoiding that and my daddy, you know said, you know That was being able to communicate was important.
So I took speech.
I made good grading speeches speech course And so I did well in the liberal arts courses And I did okay in math, but I didn't do good in chemistries matter of fact
chemistry was why I didn't get in vet school.
And it was organic chemistry, Dr. Rose.
And what the funniest part about that whole chemistry experience, because I took eight hours of chemistry my freshman year, eight more my sophomore year, so it was 16 hours of chemistry.
So I was in the chemistry building a lot.
And I remember bringing my children back to A&M once, and you could still drive around the campus then, and they were little.
And I said, I need to go show you the chemistry building.
I said, the only thing I really remember about it is it had 90 steps or something leading to the top.
Well, I found it.
I knew exactly where it was.
It had 13 steps.
And so for some reason, I thought that you had to walk forever to get up to the deck of the chemistry building.
And I remember liking Dr. Rose.
He was my organic chemistry teacher, and I thought he was a good instructor.
But I didn't do well in organic chemistry, and that was the reason I didn't get in vet school.
I mean, that was, you know, because Dr. Romaine said, Randy, we split your GPR.
We look at your liberal arts, and we go, oh, hum, and we look at your sciences, and that's what we focus on.
And you've got good grades in history and English in those courses, and you've got okay grades in math, but chemistry and physics, you know, you're a C student.
And he says, you know, we've learned that vet students who are C students in organic, you know, don't make it through vet school.
And so, you know, you're going to have a hard time.
Now, I took veterinary genetics and made an A in it.
They let me take that.

And so there was some sciences, biology I did well in because it was kind of, you know, there was bugs and animals and I could relate it to a lot of things in the ranch that I knew, farming and ranching.
But chemistry just didn't, I just didn't apply myself.
Back to that fall semester.
As you got into your company and into your outfit and started the routine, describe a typical day, class day.
What time did you get up?
What did you do when?
You know, a Monday through Friday.
Yeah.

as a fish we didn't seem to wake up real early i mean i woke up a long time before anybody else and everybody was asleep and so i did some studying and thinking early and then there was whistles and uh
you were whistle jock, and that was tough duty.
And I remember the first time I had a whistle jock, but you had to run through the halls and blow the whistle, and the first whistle was wake up, I guess.
And then it was about 20 minutes later, there was a second whistle, or it was two whistles, the guy would, you'd go through and you'd blow twice, and that meant you had five minutes to formation.
So there was 20 minutes and that's when you shaved and got dressed and everything.
And then you had this five minute call and then you had a
about a three-minute call, and then it was fallout.
And it seemed like the fallout was hollered by the first sergeant.
Mickey Ballard was my first sergeant, and I liked him a lot.
And he'd holler out, and we'd fall out, and then we'd stand there in formation and be inspected, and then we'd march to Morning Chow.
And I remember...
you know, telling my mother that not only did I not like shoes, that I didn't know how to march.
And she said, and she says, well, Randy, they'll teach you.
And I'll never forget, it was one, two, I mean, they taught us by the numbers how to left face, right face, about face, and then how to march off with our left and how to keep your thumbs down.
And what was really interesting
for 33 years in the Army, is West Pointers march well and Aggies march well, and not many other ROTC cadets know how to march.
And if you see an Air Force officer in the Army that knows how to salute, he's from A&M, because the Air Force doesn't focus on things like that, but the Air Force ROTC at A&M did,

And so when I would, you know, through the years, and I had five joint assignments, so I was with a lot of Air Force officers, and I would see one salute, I would know whether it was an Aggie just because he knew how to salute properly.

So A&M did a good job there at the beginning of teaching us the military skills and the discipline, and then we'd march to chow, and we had the longest way to march, and we'd sing our chodis, and we'd march in.
And then we ate family style.
And then there was cadets that were our waiters, the cadets that were kind of working their way through school, and they would get money for waiting tables.
And you would sit there at a table with upperclassmen and you would eat square meals forever.
It seemed like you had to eat square.
And you had, of course, you had names for all the chow.
And you passed all the chow to each other and make a round.
And if you wanted seconds, you'd have to ask for that.
But I remember not eating a lot at first because of the campusology questions.
And I kind of resented it, except as I look back, the motivation to eat.
Because the chow was pretty good.
I mean, I thought the chow was good.
And there was plenty of it.
And you were hungry.
And so the motivation to be able to eat was to learn your campusology.
And learning campusology was not, I loved the way they did it.
and I don't know when they started it and if they still do it, but it wasn't in a book.
So just if you were a good memorizer, it didn't help you.

You had to go and see Lawrence Sullivan Ross, 1838, 1898, soldier, state, or scholarly gentleman, first president of Texas A&M, and you had to go find Lawrence Sullivan Ross, and you had to copy that inscription down in your little notebook, and then you could memorize it.
And you went all over campus doing that.
So within a few days, you knew the campus or you didn't need anything.
Do you remember some trick questions, some cush questions that were kind of tricky?
Oh, I don't recall that at all, sir.
The favorite one that I have learned is, and see if you can answer this, how many stars are there in the Texas flag?
I vaguely remember that question, and I don't know what the trick answer was.
Whatever you say, the...
interrogator will answer the other one.
If you say one, he'll say no, there's two, there's one on each side.
If you say two, he'll say no, it's one, and it goes through both ways.
So the questions y'all had were real questions.
I thought were straightforward.
The other thing that I thought was good, I didn't think it at the time, but I did later, was the emphasis on everybody's names.
And so
because no one's name is...

I mean, that's the most important thing to a person, and I started figuring that out at A&M because I was never very good with names before then, but you had to know everybody's name, and you had to know all the football players' names, the first team offense, first team defense, what their number was, their name was, and what city they were from, the town where they were from in Houston and Texas.
And so...
And so all those things, the motivation was to eat, and the things they were trying to teach you were important.
The only thing that I would have done different, and I did when I was a sophomore,
was I would explain to the fish why we were doing these things.
That wasn't, no one explained why when I was a fish.
I started figuring it out, and I guess that was okay.
But I found out later in Vietnam, as an infantry company commander going from foxhole to foxhole every night, every foxhole of three to four men would say, why are we in Vietnam?
And so...
You know, I always felt it was important, when you had time, to tell people why, from a leadership skill perspective.
All right, you finished child, then you had to hurry to your eight o'clock class because you had a good distance to cover.
Yes, and the toughest part about that was whipping out, and that's another way you, if you wanted to get to class on time,
you better remember the people you met because if you knew them and you could say, howdy, Mr. Jones, sir, from, you know, Muleshoe, sir, taking veterinary medicine, sir, you passed.
You just kept going.
But if you didn't know that, you'd have to turn around and whip out.
And then depending on how obnoxious the guy was or how mad or how much he wanted to mess with you, he would walk you 100, 200, 300 yards away

away from your point of destination and to the point where almost in self-defense you really started and as soon as I would get to class I distinctly remember writing names down because I figured my learning abilities and it was really interesting because I used this for years in the military
I had to both write and listen.
I couldn't just listen.
Whatever my learning and brain housing group was, it took both of those, effective listening and writing the name.
If I would write the name down,
and think about it, there was a chance I'd remember it.
If I didn't write it down, I'd see that guy again.
He'd know me, I'd know him, and I wouldn't know his name, and we would go through that drill.
Right.
You had classes pretty well all morning.
Yes.
Then go back and fall in, march to China.
Right.
Then in the afternoon, labs.
What did you do if you had any unscheduled classes?
Well, for me, I was, there was, our company was heavy into intramurals.
And I couldn't, I wasn't big enough to play Aggie football, but we had a heck of a, you know, a touch flag football team.
And so as soon as, I mean, I don't know when practice started, but we would practice every day, you know, and there was a core group of us.
Where would y'all practice?
Well, right now there's dorms built there, but it was between 17 and the athletic dorms there was an open field.
In Henderson.
In Henderson, right.

And there was a series of marked-off fields, and I guess every company was designated one or something because we seemed to go to a different one every time, but there were several fields there that were just, I think they were only 80 yards or 60 yards long, but there were enough fields
for a good flag football practice.
And having some high school football experience, did that help you gain acceptance in the outfit?
Oh yeah, I was not a great football player through all my growing up.
I had all the heart in the world and I was determined
And the coaches would let me play because I was so dedicated in everything.
But when we started playing intramural football, I was a star.
And all of a sudden, you were the go-to guy.
and the quarterback was an upperclassman.
You very seldom had a fish quarterback, and so the quarterback's an upperclassman, and I was a receiver.
And, you know, so.
But back if you had, let's say, an unscheduled hour between 10 and 11, what did you and your buddies do?
Well, I had two wonderful friends, the Melton twins from Lamar, who were on a football scholarship.
They lived in Henderson Hall.
And there was no harassing in Henderson Hall.
And so I would, at first, I would always go to Henderson Hall any time I had a break.
And they left their room unlocked or something, and I would go in there and study.
After the other place that I found was the library, they couldn't arrest you in the library.
And so I would, a lot of times your classes were pretty close to the library, so I would just beat it to the library.
and get up on the second deck or something, those big wooden tables, and just study there in time.
Later I found out that for some reason they didn't harass you in the MSC when you were, there's all these little cubicles kind of in the MSC.
There was no prohibition against harassing, but just nobody felt like doing it.
I think the term Memorial Student Center
kind of took the edge off of the upperclassmen.
And so sometimes you could go to the MSC and do some studying.
And I was pretty conscientious about all that.
I mean, I wasn't a good student.
I mean, I wasn't a great student, and I didn't like school.
But I knew that I wanted to be a veterinarian, and I knew I had to make certain grades.
And school was hard work for me.
And so I was pretty diligent in just trying to study.
Plus, I didn't like staying up late at night.
I was not a night owl.
I got up early in the morning, but I went to bed with chickens back then.
And so I had to do a lot of my studying during the day.
All right.
You're getting involved in all these activities, and then...
here come some of the first big Aggie traditional events.
I presume Yale practice would have been about, would have happened before a Silver Taps or anything like that.
Well, yeah, and of course, starting in the fall, you had your football games, so you had your Yale practice before those.
Where was Yale practice held then?
It seemed like, to me, it was held over at the Grove.
At the Grove, okay.
And it wasn't at midnight, was it?
No, midnight, there was no such thing as midnight yell practice, because it was good, because I wouldn't have been awake.
You know, because nothing happens after 2100 worth of staying awake for.
And so, no, and I remember, you know, I liked...
all that stuff, you know, that was okay, you know.
Alright, then do you remember going to your first home football games?
Well, I remember going, you know, marching into all the games.
And I remember the first games that were in September.
I don't know who we were playing, but I remember we were on the east side facing the west side.
And you stood up at all of the games.
You never sat down.
And I remember saying that I never was as tired as a player when I played nine years of Texas football.
I was never as tired as a player as I was as a fan
because of the way, you know, the focus of the game.
So, you know, marching in, falling in, you know, with your company, all the, you know, that was kind of all hard work, you know, really.
Did you have any dates?
Yeah, Jeannie and I, my wife, we dated in high school.
Okay.
And so we continued to date, and...

She had a real good friend in Navasota, so she could come up on the bus from Houston to Navasota and stay with her friend, and then I could go down and get her Saturday mornings and bring her up to the games.
But I don't recall...
I don't recall doing that a whole lot, but she does.
So, I mean, we did do that.
Even as a fish?
I think so, yeah.
I think so.
Now, then after the game was over, what did Aggie freshmen do on a Saturday night?
Well, the first couple of games, you know, we were restricted to the campus.
And so we just, you know, went back to the barracks and
And I just remember just kind of being in the barracks.
Now, the only exception to that, and I don't know, Billy Provine, my roommate's older brother, was a junior in the Air Force, ROTC.
And so he had a car, Chevrolet Impala.
And Billy loved his Budweiser and would...

sneak out after the games, get his brother's car, I guess in agreement with his brother, and this was a dry county back then, but Billy would drive out to a place, and I swear it was called Pop's Place, but I don't know for sure, but it was out towards Austin, you know, past Snook or somewhere out there, and Billy would drink Budweiser.
Well, Billy was a good man, but, you know, he would drink too much.
I was a non-drinker, absolute teetotaler.
And so Pop would call back to the barracks, get the CQ.
We didn't have phones in our rooms or anything.
CQ would send the CQ runner, and they'd come get me, and I'd go down the hall, and I'd talk to the proprietor there, Pops.
And this was another motivation to get my Jeep, because then I would...

talk either talk to CQ or I would sneak out and I would go get Billy and the first time I'll never forget going out there to get him you know he went out in his car and I went out in my jeep or in a car another car and drove up there and I was trying to figure out how I was going to get both cars back because I knew he couldn't drive
And I walked in there, and there he was at the bar.
And Billy was just a wonderful human being, but he had drank too much.
And so I said, Billy, it's time to go.
Let's get on back.
And he'd look, and he'd say, I need one more beer.
And Pop says, he doesn't have any money.
And I'd say, Billy, you don't have any money?
And I'm not going to give you any money.
And so Billy, the first night, looked at Pop, and he says, Pop, if I can bite my eyeball, can I have a beer?
Pop looked at him and said, Billy, I don't know what the scam is, but it's worth it.
So we poured him a Budweiser.
And Billy savored this Budweiser for 15 minutes.
And at the end, Pop says, OK, Billy, bite your eyeball.
Billy pops out an artificial eye and bites it.
He had had a hunting accident.
He was a wonderful hunter.
And his brother, they were dove hunting in Louisiana, had shot and shot his eye out.
And so he had an artificial eye.
And I knew he had an artificial eye, but I didn't know you could pop those things out.
And so Billy popped it out and bit it.
And then he told the story about it.
And then Pop said, well, how did it happen and everything?
And so, you know, then I say, okay, Billy, let's go.
And Billy looks at Pop and he says, Pop, I'd like another Budweiser.
And Pop says, Billy, you've had too many.
You don't have any money, and it's time to go.
And he says, if I can bite my other eyeball,
Can I have another beer?
Well, Pop knew he'd driven out there.
Knew he wasn't blind.
And he says, Billy, I have no idea what the scam is, but it is worth another Budweiser.
So he pours him another Budweiser.
Billy savors that Budweiser for 15 minutes, and then Pop says, okay, Billy, what's the deal?
Billy takes out his false teeth, and he bites his other eyes.
He'd been in a traffic accident, and he had both false uppers and lowers.
Oh, my goodness.
And so we went through college.
We went to all the, I mean, Billy went through college with free beers doing that.
And I participated in this ritual.
100 times in four years.
And then I had to play straight faced.
And it was always me because I was always picking Billy up at some place or the other.
But I don't really remember any big things.
Sometimes they let you have a pass to go to that movie theater in Northgate right across from 17.
There was a Saturday night campus theater.
I remember we could go, we were living in 17, so they'd give us a pass to go over there, and I think we did that.
But as soon as the grades were out, and I had good enough grades to have my, as soon as the game was over, I headed to the ranch.
So I didn't spend, matter of fact, back then, there was no girls until my sophomore year, and my sophomore year, 64, I think it was only nine on campus.
And I didn't even see one until my junior year, I think.
And so what A&M was back then was leaving A&M.
I mean, that's what you did.
As a matter of fact, anybody that stayed around, they called them whole rats, and you worried about them.
You know, they were depressed or...

or they were getting down because what the normal Aggie did was leave A&M, which is a great thing about bringing the females because we lost a lot of cadets on Highway 6 and others and car crashes that if we'd have had more activities on campus, those kids might not have been traveling.
If you were here on all weekend, what did you do on Sunday?
Well, I was a member of St. Luke's Methodist Church in Houston, a lifetime member, but I went to the A&M Methodist Church, which was right by the post office.
For four years, my box number was 1207.
And I'd go by the post office and go there to the Methodist Church.
And I don't remember the minister's name, but I know he was a good guy, and I liked Sundays over there.
I don't recall ever going to the A&M Chapel or anything like that.
I mean, being a Methodist, that was a natural thing for me to do.
Did you go on Sunday night?
No, because Sunday night, you know, you always had your company meetings because they wanted to make sure everybody was back and everybody was okay.
And so Sunday nights seemed to be taken up with getting ready for the next week.
So I don't remember going to church on Sunday nights.
Court trip.
Remember any of that fall?
Well, there was two.
We went one to Houston, one to Fort Worth.
And the one to Houston, I'll distinctly remember.

because Captain Kieschnick, our company commander, right before the Eyes Right, whoever we were doing Eyes Right for, and he, you know, we're marching down Main Street in Houston, and I remember it was wet, you know, we're playing rice, of course, and...
He spun around, and I was way back because I was a rear-ranked Rudy, so I didn't see this.
I just heard about it, and I saw all the results of it.
But he turned around in front of the guide-on bearer there to, I think, speak to the front line of seniors on something.
And when he spun back, his spurs locked, and he fell, and we marched over him.
And see...
I think the first two ranks parted and didn't touch him, but then after that, you didn't know he was there, so he got marched on.

And so then, you know, he was, and it was wet, and, you know, he had on his, I mean, he was a good-looking man, too, and a good-looking uniform, and he had to get up and run to the front, and so when he did the passing review, I remember seeing the pictures, because there was pictures taken of every passing review, and
He had these muds, he had footprints all over his uniform where people had accidentally, because I think most of us liked Captain Kishnick.
But he was marched on by his own company.
And that's what I remember of that Corps trip was him tripping to the point that
As an officer, I was in many a parade.
And you would spin around like that to face the troops at times.
And I was always conscious of being careful.
Now, I didn't have on spurs.
But I was careful that I didn't lock my heels and fall in front of my men, because I always felt bad for my company commander.
On the Corps trips to Houston, were you expected to house a bunch of Aggies at your?
In my house?
Yeah, I did, too.
About how many might it be?
Well, I was fortunate.
I lived in a big house, and my brother was away at college, and so we had, I don't know, I don't,
There was more than one carload, though.
A lot of guys.
Eight or ten?
Yes, right.
And my mother enjoyed it all, and my daddy tolerated it.
And how did Aggies behave as guests at someone's house?
Well, I pretty well picked who I wanted, and they all knew that,
that I was from a non-drinking family, so they behaved themselves.
Because we had heard about all the drinking at court trips, and I said, guys, my family doesn't drink, and I don't drink, and if you're going to be in my house, you can't drink.
And so you can't come home drunk.
I said, my daddy was a football player at LSU.
He was a boxer at LSU.
And we got a six-foot brick wall, and he'll throw you over it.
Now, was it normal on Sunday morning that they would get up and head away?
Well, because I was from Houston, I had dates for them all after the game, and then several of them would go see their girlfriends again.
